Chapter 0
Introduction
These notes cover the core introductory topics in linear algebra. In particular, it denes and states the major theorems for
nite-dimensional vector spaces, as well as dening important terms for all mathematics such as eigenvalues, inner products,
operator theory, and more.
The lecture notes are based o two main sources. The overall outline and the major statements of theorems and denitions
are based o lecture notes from Dr. Vrilly-Alvarado during the Fall 2019 teaching of Rices course MATH 354 Honors Linear
Algebra. These notes are supplemented by notes and exercises from Axlers Linear Algebra Done Right.

1.2 Proofs by Induction
Theorem 1.2.1: Principle of Mathematical Induction II
Let P (n) be a statement indexed by n N. Suppose that
1. P(1) is true. (The base case)
2. If P (k) is true for some k N, then P (k + 1) is true. (The inductive hypothesis)
Then P (n) is true for all n N.
Theorem 1.2.2: Principle of Mathematical Induction III
Let Q(n) be a statement indexed by n N. Suppose that

2. If Q(k) is true for some k N, then Q(k + 1) is true. (The inductive hypothesis)
